{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Why\nOnce rebar owns the OIDC provider + the domain-wide SSO stack, rebar's infra docs must describe them so the ownership, dependencies, and operations (secret rotation, incident revoke) live in rebar's tree, not snap's dead repo.\n\n## What\n- Update `docs/gerrit-aws-setup.md`: note rebar now OWNS the GitHub OIDC provider (was \"already exists in the account\"), and document the adopted wildcard cert + auth_host SSO stack.\n- Fix the stale comment in `infra/terraform/iam.tf` that says the OIDC provider \"already exists in the account ... assumes it exists\" now that rebar creates/owns it.\n- Add an ADR under `docs/adr/` recording the snap→rebar re-homing decision (why adopt vs tear down, name-preservation tradeoff, state migration).\n- Add an SSO operations runbook under `infra/runbooks/` adapted from snap's `auth/RUNBOOK.md` (architecture, secrets `/auth-solutions/*`, cookie-key rotation, Google-secret rotation, incident revoke lever, and how to protect a new rebar subdomain via the reusable `infra/terraform/modules/sso-gate` module — which the terraform story adopts into rebar as code alongside the auth host, so the runbook references an existing module).\n- Note the retag (`project=snap-demo` → `Project=rebar`).\n\n## Scope\nDocumentation only. Depends on the terraform adoption story landing (or landing alongside).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] `docs/gerrit-aws-setup.md` documents rebar's ownership of the OIDC provider + the SSO stack.\n- [ ] `infra/terraform/iam.tf`'s OIDC comment no longer claims the provider is externally owned.\n- [ ] An ADR records the re-homing decision + tradeoffs.\n- [ ] An `infra/runbooks/` SSO runbook covers architecture, secrets, rotation, and incident revoke."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784047984075226001,"uuid":"f4df9507-c823-45ec-95a3-e7df54938a5a"}